<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Carapace (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Metaplax elegans De Man, 1888 (A-C NCHUZOOL 15496, male, 12.7 mm), M. longipes Stimpson, 1858 (D-F ZRC 2019.0581, male, 14.9 mm), M. sheni Gordon, 1930 (G-I NCHUZOOL 15466, male, 9.9 mm), and M. tredecim Tweedie, 1950 (J-L paratype, ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18, 16.2 mm). A, D, G, J, A carapace B, E, H, K left infraorbital ridge C, F, I, L outer view of right cheliped. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343945" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2">Figs 2J</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Metaplax tredecim Tweedie, 1950. A, F Dorsal view B ventral view C left infraorbital ridge D right cheliped E right side of carapace showing the five teeth of lateral margin. A-E paratype male (CW 16.2 mm; ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18; Labuan) F male (CW 16.5 mm; NCHUZOOL 15473; Hong Kong) G male (CW 15.4 mm; NCHUZOOL 15475; Labuan, Malaysia) H, I male (18.2 mm; NCHUZOOL 15705; Hong Kong) G-I color in life. Scale bars: 2.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343949" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6">6A, F, G</figureCitation>
) subquadrate, 1.35 times broader than long (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">N</emphasis>
= 39, SD = 0.03), regions defined by shallow grooves, slightly inflated, surface pitted; front nearly straight, medially slightly concave; lateral margin mildly convex, posteriorly converging, cut into five teeth, anterior two pronounced, quadrate, posterior two inconspicuous; posterolateral facet slightly depressed, behind second notch decorated with two short oblique granular ridges. Infraorbital ridge (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Metaplax elegans De Man, 1888 (A-C NCHUZOOL 15496, male, 12.7 mm), M. longipes Stimpson, 1858 (D-F ZRC 2019.0581, male, 14.9 mm), M. sheni Gordon, 1930 (G-I NCHUZOOL 15466, male, 9.9 mm), and M. tredecim Tweedie, 1950 (J-L paratype, ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18, 16.2 mm). A, D, G, J, A carapace B, E, H, K left infraorbital ridge C, F, I, L outer view of right cheliped. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343945" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2">Figs 2K</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Metaplax tredecim Tweedie, 1950. A, F Dorsal view B ventral view C left infraorbital ridge D right cheliped E right side of carapace showing the five teeth of lateral margin. A-E paratype male (CW 16.2 mm; ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18; Labuan) F male (CW 16.5 mm; NCHUZOOL 15473; Hong Kong) G male (CW 15.4 mm; NCHUZOOL 15475; Labuan, Malaysia) H, I male (18.2 mm; NCHUZOOL 15705; Hong Kong) G-I color in life. Scale bars: 2.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343949" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6">6C</figureCitation>
) markedly sexually dimorphic: in males medial four or five roughly same size, decreasing in breadth laterally, laterally of a row of seven or eight small, rounded, isomorphic, tubercles; females with 21-27 small isomorphic tubercles. Chelipeds (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Metaplax elegans De Man, 1888 (A-C NCHUZOOL 15496, male, 12.7 mm), M. longipes Stimpson, 1858 (D-F ZRC 2019.0581, male, 14.9 mm), M. sheni Gordon, 1930 (G-I NCHUZOOL 15466, male, 9.9 mm), and M. tredecim Tweedie, 1950 (J-L paratype, ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18, 16.2 mm). A, D, G, J, A carapace B, E, H, K left infraorbital ridge C, F, I, L outer view of right cheliped. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343945" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2">Figs 2L</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Metaplax tredecim Tweedie, 1950. A, F Dorsal view B ventral view C left infraorbital ridge D right cheliped E right side of carapace showing the five teeth of lateral margin. A-E paratype male (CW 16.2 mm; ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18; Labuan) F male (CW 16.5 mm; NCHUZOOL 15473; Hong Kong) G male (CW 15.4 mm; NCHUZOOL 15475; Labuan, Malaysia) H, I male (18.2 mm; NCHUZOOL 15705; Hong Kong) G-I color in life. Scale bars: 2.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343949" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6">6D</figureCitation>
) stout, symmetrical, palm 2.3 times longer than broad, length of palm approximately 1.6 times of length of dactyl (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">N</emphasis>
= 12), meri slightly dilated anteriorly, lined with minute denticles along the margin; chela surface finely granulated, along cutting edges both fingers unarmed. Ambulatory legs slender, elongated, meri of P3 and P4 tomentum-covered on distal half, and propodi of P2 to P4 with thick mat of setae. G1 (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Metaplax elegans De Man, 1888 (A-D NCHUZOOL 15496, male, 12.7 mm), right G 1; M. longipes Stimpson, 1858 (E-H ZRC 2019.0581, male, 14.9 mm), right G 1; M. sheni Gordon, 1930 (I-L NCHUZOOL 15466, male, 9.9 mm), right G 1; and M. tredecim Tweedie, 1950 (M-P paratype, ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18, 16.2 mm), left G 1. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-H, M-P); 0.2 mm (I-L)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343950" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure7">
Fig. 7
<normalizedToken originalValue="M–P">M-P</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) elongated, slender, almost straight.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Southeast and East Asia: northern Borneo (Labuan, Malaysia; Brunei), Vietnam (Quang Ninh; Khanh Hoa), and South China (Hong Kong) (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Collection sites (solid symbols) for species of the genus Metaplax used in this study: green rhombus for M. elegans; red circles for M. longipes; blue triangles for M. sheni; and purple squares for M. tredecim. Empty symbols mean the additional records from references (see synonym lists for each species)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343944" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure1">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In Hong Kong, in comparison to 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. longipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. longipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tredecim" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tredecim">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tredecim</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tends to occur in habitats of coarser, grittier substrates, with less freshwater input, and frequently on open sandflats rather unsheltered by mangroves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Identification of the 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Varunidae" genus="Metaplax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metaplax tredecim" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tredecim">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Metaplax tredecim</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had been confusing, particularly based on the number of teeth along the lateral margin of the carapace. 
<bibRefCitation author="Tweedie, MWF" journalOrPublisher="Sarawak Museum Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="338 - 369" refId="B85" refString="Tweedie, MWF, 1950. Grapsoid crabs from Labuan and Sarawak. Sarawak Museum Journal 5: 338 - 369" title="Grapsoid crabs from Labuan and Sarawak." volume="5" year="1950">Tweedie (1950</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 6) showed merely three conspicuous lobes, the posterior one occupying more than half of carapace length. However, as noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Davie, PJF" journalOrPublisher="Raffles Bulletin of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="379 - 386" refId="B15" refString="Davie, PJF, Nguyen, VX, 2003. A new species of Metaplax (Crustacea: Brachyura: Varunidae: Cyclograpsinae) from Vietnam. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 51: 379 - 386" title="A new species of Metaplax (Crustacea: Brachyura: Varunidae: Cyclograpsinae) from Vietnam." volume="51" year="2003">Davie and Nguyen (2003)</bibRefCitation>
, members of the genus often have the structures around the posterolateral facet obscured by setae-trapped sediments, and not visible unless carefully denuded. Reexamination of a paratype male (16.2 mm; ZRC 1964.7.14.4-18), after denudation, showed the lateral margin to be interrupted by 4 notches (hence 5 teeth) (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Metaplax elegans De Man, 1888 (A-C NCHUZOOL 15496, male, 12.7 mm), M. longipes Stimpson, 1858 (D-F ZRC 2019.0581, male, 14.9 mm), M. sheni Gordon, 1930 (G-I NCHUZOOL 15466, male, 9.9 mm), and M. tredecim Tweedie, 1950 (J-L paratype, ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18, 16.2 mm). A, D, G, J, A carapace B, E, H, K left infraorbital ridge C, F, I, L outer view of right cheliped. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343945" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure2">Figs 2J</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Metaplax tredecim Tweedie, 1950. A, F Dorsal view B ventral view C left infraorbital ridge D right cheliped E right side of carapace showing the five teeth of lateral margin. A-E paratype male (CW 16.2 mm; ZRC 1964.7.14.4 - 18; Labuan) F male (CW 16.5 mm; NCHUZOOL 15473; Hong Kong) G male (CW 15.4 mm; NCHUZOOL 15475; Labuan, Malaysia) H, I male (18.2 mm; NCHUZOOL 15705; Hong Kong) G-I color in life. Scale bars: 2.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/343949" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.877.38300.figure6">6A, E</figureCitation>
), the posterior two being inconspicuously defined by the last notch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
As mentioned above, two forms, differing in the number of tubercles or lobes on the infraorbital ridge, were recognized in specimens identified with 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. longipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. longipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dai, AY" journalOrPublisher="China Ocean Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B13" refString="Dai, AY, Yang, SL, Song, YZ, Chen, GX, 1986. Crabs of the China seas. China Ocean Press, Beijing" title="Crabs of the China seas." year="1986">Dai et al. (1986)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Dai, AY" journalOrPublisher="China Ocean Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B12" refString="Dai, AY, Yang, SL, 1991. Crabs of the China Seas. China Ocean Press, Beijing" title="Crabs of the China Seas." year="1991">Dai and Yang (1991)</bibRefCitation>
. We confirmed that specimens from the study area, characterized by the possession of about 17 tubercles or lobes closely represent 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tredecim" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tredecim">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tredecim</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. There is little doubt that the material studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dai, AY" journalOrPublisher="China Ocean Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B13" refString="Dai, AY, Yang, SL, Song, YZ, Chen, GX, 1986. Crabs of the China seas. China Ocean Press, Beijing" title="Crabs of the China seas." year="1986">Dai et al. (1986)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Dai, AY" journalOrPublisher="China Ocean Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B12" refString="Dai, AY, Yang, SL, 1991. Crabs of the China Seas. China Ocean Press, Beijing" title="Crabs of the China Seas." year="1991">Dai and Yang (1991)</bibRefCitation>
included two species, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. longipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. longipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tredecim" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tredecim">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tredecim</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B8">Chertoprud et al. (2012)</bibRefCitation>
recorded &quot; 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. longipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. longipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; from Nha Phu, southeastern Vietnam. However, given the infraorbital ridge with 17 tubercles and the chelipeds with the length of palm/the length of dactyl ratio about 1.5 (estimated from their plate 47F on page 295), this record is suspected to represent 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tredecim" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tredecim">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tredecim</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead (see Table 
<tableCitation captionStartId="T2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/2CCAB3CE4375FA31438947C2ED9CEA7C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableUuid="2CCAB3CE4375FA31438947C2ED9CEA7C">2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
